## Protected Files — NEVER Modify Without Explicit Per-File Directive

The following files must **not** be read-then-rewritten, patched, or overwritten by any agent under any circumstances unless the user names the file explicitly and approves the specific change:

| File | Why protected |
|---|---|
| `.envrc` | Deliberate opt-in design. Modifying it silently changes shell environment for all users. |
| `.gitignore` | Changing exclusion rules can accidentally expose secrets or generated artefacts to git history. |
| `pyproject.toml` / `package.json` | Dependency pins and build metadata are versioned decisions; silent changes break reproducibility. |
| lock files (`uv.lock`, `package-lock.json`, etc.) | Generated by the package manager; never hand-edit. |
| `.github/workflows/*.yml` | CI pipeline changes affect all contributors and require explicit review. |

**Rules:**
- Read these files freely for context. Do not write them.
- If a task seems to require touching one of these files, **stop and ask** — do not infer approval from a broader instruction.
- `git show origin/main:<file>` is the authoritative original. Never reconstruct from memory.
- Claiming a write "restores the original" does not substitute for checking git.

**Session startup check — `.envrc` permission guard:**
At the start of every session, if `.envrc` exists in the repo root, run:
```bash
ls -l .envrc
```
If the permissions are **not** `-r--r--r--` (i.e. not `444`), **stop immediately** and tell the user:

> `.envrc` is not read-only (current permissions: `<permissions>`).
> Run `chmod 444 .envrc` to protect it from accidental agent modification before continuing.

Do not proceed with any other work until the user has acknowledged this. Do not set the permissions yourself.

